<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   French Foreign Minister Holds Talks in Amman </TI></H3>
<H4>   Juppe Arrives, Makes Statements </H4>
<F P=102> JN1202154894 Amman Radio Jordan Network in Arabic 1400 GMT 
12 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1202154894 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman Radio Jordan Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] French Foreign Affairs Minister Alain Juppe has 
said Jordanian-French relations are distinguished, constantly 
growing, and getting deeper. He said he is satisfied with the 
move to allow French firms to invest in Jordan. 
  Upon arrival in Amman today, Juppe said that France is 
looking forward to the establishment of a comprehensive peace in 
the region and that his visit to Jordan is based on France's 
concern for supporting the peace process. He added: France has 
a role to play in the peace process, particularly in the 
framework of the multilateral talks and the committees in which 
it is involved, such as economic development, water, and refugee 
committees. 
  Juppe said France is seeking to help Jordan reschedule its 
foreign debt; the amount of which is a burden to the Jordanian 
economy. 
  He said France is working through NATO to put an end to the 
suffering of people in Bosnia and is determined not to miss any 
opportunity to achieve peace there. The recent NATO decision, 
he said, has restored confidence and there are encouraging signs 
now from the parties to the conflict that they will listen to 
the voice of logic, including the handing over of some heavy 
weapons to the United Nations. 
  Juppe was received at Amman civilian airport by Dr. Fawwaz 
Abu-al-Ghanam, acting minister of state for foreign affairs; the 
French ambassador in Amman; and senior Foreign Ministry and 
French Embassy staff. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

