<H3> <TI>   Army Withdraws From Kanpur as Situation Improves </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1502163094 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 1530 
GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1502163094 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In Uttar Pradesh, with the continued improvement of 
the situation in Kanpur, the Army has been completely withdrawn 
from the city. Our Kanpur correspondent, Raghunandan 
Chaturvedi, quoting official sources, says 22 companies of 
paramilitary and police are keeping a watch in sensitive areas. 
In the (Babupurva) locality, the curfew has been relaxed for 
three hours for the first time today in (Dankapurva), except in 
blocks and transport mega pockets. The situation continued to 
be peaceful during curfew relaxation. The state government has 
constituted a one-man commission to go into the incidents in 
Varanasi during the first week of this month. 
  Meanwhile, Banaras Hindu University administration has 
ordered an inquiry into the death of a student in the university 
hospital last Sunday [13 February] and the incidents of violence 
which followed his death. A retired judge of the Allahabad High 
Court will conduct the inquiry. The bundh [strike] called by 
the Students Union in Varanasi against the indefinite closure of 
the Banaras Hindu University has had a mixed response today. 
Police arrested over 50 persons, including the Students Union 
leader, for defying prohibitory orders under Section 144. 

</TEXT>

