<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Truce </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1602111194 London AL-HAYAH in Arabic 15 Feb 94 p 8 </F>
<F P=103> PM1602111194 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-HAYAH </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Ahmad Muwaffaq Zaydan report: "Hekmatyar and Rabbani Accept </F>
Four-day Truce Beginning Today"] 
  [Excerpts] Peshawar from Ahmad Muwaffaq Zaydan; Geneva 
(United Nations), REUTER -- After six weeks of fierce fighting, 
the two warring parties in Kabul have agreed on a four-day truce 
to make way for a study of the causes of the war and ways of 
resolving the crisis between President Borhanoddin Rabbani and 
Prime Minister Golboddin Hekmatyar. 
  Afghan Reconcilian Committee Chairman Jalaloddin Haqqani 
told 
AL-HAYAH yesterday that the truce in Kabul "will begin at 0500 
Tuesday [15 February] and will last for four days." 
  Haqqani, who heads a committee consisting of some 100 
commanders and ulema, added: "We have, from both sides, written 
assurances of adherence to the cease-fire and cooperation for 
the sake of probing the main causes of the crisis." 
  Asked by AL-HAYAH if the cease-fire would also apply to the 
Uzbek forces against whom the Afghan president declared jihad 
and refused to agree a cease-fire with, Haqqani said: "There 
will be a cease-fire between the camps of Rabbani and 
Hekmatyar." He reaffirmed that both parties to the conflict had 
agreed to a truce. 
  Prime Minister Golboddin Hekmatyar told AL-HAYAH that "the 
Higher Coordination Council has agreed to a cease-fire provided 
it is used to find a mechanism for the settlement of the current 
crisis, as follows: Unconditional resignation of the president 
(Rabbani), declaration of Kabul a demilitarized zone, removal of 
the armed units from it within a week, and the formation of a 
provisional government within two weeks." [passage omitted] 
  Haqqani made an appeal through AL-HAYAH to the Islamic 
governments and organizations to provide urgent aid for the 
Afghan capital. Emotionally, he said: "The situation is 
extremely tragic, with scores of families without shelter, 
clothes, or food. The Muslims must help in this critical period." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

