<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   France's Juppe Continues Visit, Meets Palestinians </TI></H3>
<H4>   Juppe Urges Adherence to Accord Schedule </H4>
<F P=102> LD1602093094 Paris France-Inter Radio Network in French 0700 
GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1602093094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-Inter Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Alain Juppe spoke about peace at the end of his 
three-day visit to Israel. The French foreign minister would 
like the Israeli Government and the PLO to keep to the schedule 
of the agreement signed in Washington on 13 September of last 
year. Otherwise, Juppe said, the supporters of war may have the 
last word: 
  [Begin Juppe recording] A failure would be a tragedy; 
everyone agrees about that. Everything must be done in order to 
have every chance of succeeding. I have already said that time 
does not work for those who want peace; it works for those 
against it. We believe that the announced schedule must be kept 
to as much as possible. I hope that a global agreement on 
Palestinian autonomy and its implementation will be reached in 
the near future. 
  I believe that the global atmosphere must be changed, that 
measures of detente and trust must be developed. This is why, 
when I went to Gaza, I advocated the freezing of settlements in 
the occupied territories, as well as the imminent release and 
rehabilitation of prisoners. I would like to add, however, that 
I also understand Israel's concern after the historic leap that 
was made last September. I understand the concern of the people 
for their security. [end recording] 
  That was Alain Juppe speaking in Jerusalem last night during 
his news conference recorded by Pierre Weill. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

