<F P=100> SYRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Israel Said Continuing To `Confuse the Issues' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1502150494 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 15 Feb 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> PM1502150494 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Salwa al-Ustuwan: "Syria Not Optimistic, Accuses </F>
Israel of Confusing Issues"] 
  [Excerpt] Damascus -- On the eve of the resumption of the 
Washington talks, which begin today among leaders of the Arab 
delegations and Israel in the framework of the Middle East peace 
process, Israel continues to adopt fluctuating and unfixed 
positions vis-a-vis the foundations of the peace process and the 
achievement of progress on the tracks involving it and the Arab 
parties. In fact it preempted the negotiations by casting doubt 
on their results, describing them as futile. 
  Syria yesterday expressed a kind of pessimism about the 
possibility of achieving any progress. A Syrian official has 
told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT that Israel continues to confuse the 
issues as a result of its position rejecting peace and the 
separation policy it is pursuing, which has resulted in the Oslo 
and Cairo agreements with the PLO. Through this policy it is 
seeking to infiltrate Arab ranks. The official pointed out that 
Israel's request to raise the level of representation in the 
negotiations on the Syrian track centers on its reliance on the 
concessions offered to it by the Palestinian side, since this 
request came immediately after the Cairo agreement. He said: 
No matter how many agreements of that kind are concluded, they 
cannot lead to a solution in the Middle East, especially as the 
U.S. Administration and the world are committed to the 
foundations of the peace process and a comprehensive and just 
peace is an international demand just as it is an Arab and 
regional demand. 
  The Syrian official described the new Washington round of 
negotiations as sensitive and delicate. He said they are bound 
to reveal the new Israeli orientation, even though nothing has 
yet been issued by Israel to indicate that it is offering 
something new through its delegation to Washington. 
  The official said that Syria continues to receive from 
Washington assurances about the U.S. commitment to the 
foundations of the peace process. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

