<F P=101> Kuwait </F>
<H3> <TI>   Information Minister on Reorganizing Gulf Priorities </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1502103494 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 12 Feb 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM1502103494 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Husayn 'Abd-al-Rahman: "Kuwaiti Information </F>
Minister Tells AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT: We Are Seeking To Reorganize 
Our Gulf Priorities and Working for Posterity"] 
  [Text] Kuwait -- Kuwaiti Information Minister Shaykh Sa'ud 
Nasir al-Sabah has stressed in a statement to AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT 
that he "has never contemplated closing any Kuwaiti newspaper or 
magazine by an Information Ministry decision." He said that 
that "falls under the powers of the court, to which all 
publication issues are referred." 
  Expressing his eagerness not to disturb relations between 
Kuwait and Arab states by publishing reports insulting them, 
Shaykh Sa'ud al-Sabah, who is visiting London today, said: 
"Just as we do not accept the publication of articles or topics 
insulting Kuwait and its people, it is natural for us to 
appreciate the position of the states which are not satisfied 
with what our newspapers are publishing about them." 
  Shaykh Sa'id, who was Kuwait's ambassador to London and 
Washington before his appointment as information minister in the 
current Kuwaiti Government, said that "the Gulf region is 
experiencing critical conditions caused by the Iraqi regime." 
He stressed "the need to reorganize our Gulf priorities and 
seek to unite the Gulf Cooperation Council states, including the 
military strategy." 
  Speaking about Iran's role, the Kuwaiti information minister 
said that Iran is one of the states which should "join us in 
safeguarding Gulf security and stability." 
  Shaykh Sa'ud stressed that "we are thinking about the 
region's conditions now but are working and planning for 
posterity." He emphasized that "Kuwait is ready for all 
possibilities that may arise from a change of conditions in Iraq 
and the downfall of Saddam Husayn's regime." 

</TEXT>

