<H3> <TI>   Birri Visits South; Army Positions `Reinforced' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1002175194 Beirut Radio Lebanon in Arabic 1630 GMT 10 Feb 
94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1002175194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beirut Radio Lebanon </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Nabih Birri, speaker of the Chamber of Deputies, 
went to the south this morning to follow up developments there 
in light of the continuing Israeli military escalation. He 
listened to security briefings about the attacks and telephoned 
Foreign Minister Faris Buwayz and Defense Minister Muhsin Dallul. 
  Israeli occupation forces continue to make the security 
situation in the south and western al-Biqa' worse, amid mounting 
fears of renewed Israeli attacks on the liberated areas. Since 
morning, the Israelis have shelled Frun, al-Ghanduriyah, Zawtar 
al-Sharqiyah, Zawtar al-Gharbiyah, Bra'shit, and Haddathah. 
Israeli reinforcements continue to pour into the occupied 
border strip. 
  In the past few hours, the Lebanese Army reinforced its 
positions in Marj al-Zahur, Mimis, and western al-Biqa' with men 
and weapons in anticipation of any eventuality. 
  Elsewhere today, Timor Goksel, spokesman for the UN Interim 
Force in Lebanon, said five Nepalese soldiers were wounded, one 
of them seriously, when their military vehicle overturned 
yesterday near al-Ghanduriyah in Tyre. 

</TEXT>

