<F P=100> Libya </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tripoli Said To Offer Aozou Strip for POWs' Return </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1602112594 London AL-HAYAH in Arabic 15 Feb 94 pp 1, 4 </F>
<F P=103> PM1602112594 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-HAYAH </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Libya Asks Chad To Hand Over POW's </F>
in Return for Aozou Strip"] 
  [Excerpts] London, AL-HAYAH -- A Chadian diplomatic source 
in Tripoli has confirmed that Libya is asking Chad to hand over 
500 Libyan POW's, who are now in the United States, in return 
for the Aozou strip. Meanwhile, the opposition's National Front 
for the Salvation of Libya [NFSL], which these POW's 
subsequently joined, has decided to appoint Colonel Salih 
Muhammad al-Habbuni commander in chief of the Libyan National 
Army [LNA] (the NFSL's military arm) in place of Colonel 
Khalifah Haftar. [passage omitted] 
  Yesterday the NFSL leadership issued a statement saying it 
had decided to appoint al-Habbuni commander in chief of the 
opposition army and Staff Lieutenant Colonel 'Abdallah 
al-Shaykhi deputy commander in chief. The statement said that 
the army represented the "NFSL's armed forces and was 
established by a decision of the Permanent Bureau 21 June 1988 
after a large number of Libyan senior officers, warrant 
officers, and soldiers deployed in Chad announced that they were 
joining the NFSL." The statement also said that "Col. Haftar 
had held the post of commander in chief of that army by a 
decision of the NFSL's Executive Committee, until he announced 
his withdrawal from the NFSL" on 11 February 1994. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

