<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Libyan Ambassador Denies Link to Diplomat's Murder </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN1502182894 Amman AKHIR KHABAR in Arabic 15-16 Feb 94 p23 </F>
<F P=103> JN1502182894 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AKHIR KHABAR </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Amman, AKHIR KHABAR -- The Libyan ambassador in 
Amman has denied Libya had any connection with the killing of 
the diplomat Na'ib al-Ma'ayitah. 
  The ambassador told AKHIR KHABAR that Libyan-Jordanian 
relations are extremely good. He said there is a plot that is 
intended to harm Libyan-Jordanian ties, saying that the plot 
that is being hatched is bigger than the Arab people. He said 
colonialist nations seek to create problems and sow discord in 
order to preoccupy the Arab people with bilateral and trilateral 
problems, in order to peddle their solutions and policies in the 
region. 
  Answering a question about any official contacts between the 
Libyans and the Jordanian Government, the ambassador said: The 
Jordanian Government knows the truth. There is no need for any 
contacts. It is difficult to discuss denial and confirmation 
between brothers. 
  Regarding the party that leaked the information to AFP, the 
ambassador said: We do not know who is behind this. But 
imagine that the United States has recently said that Libya is 
conspiring against its security. Who would believe that? 
Imagine a Third World nation conspiring against the security of 
a superpower? 
  The ambassador concluded: Reason must prevail in this 
region. The United States and the colonialist countries should 
know that we are not little children anymore. We should analyze 
things. Dialogue is not a bad approach. 

</TEXT>

