<F P=100> Pakistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bhutto Rejects Indian Allegations of Interference </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1502153494 Islamabad PTV Television Network in English 
1400 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1502153494 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad PTV Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The prime minister, Ms. Benazir Bhutto, today 
refuted a statement attributed to her and said during her 
interview with BBC, she was making comparison between the 
situation in Indian-held Kashmir and the Indian Punjab. In an 
informal talk with newsmen in Islamabad today, the prime 
minister said what she had told BBC was that Kashmir was a 
disputed territory and if Pakistan had not interfered in India's 
internal affairs when it was facing problems in east Punjab, 
then how could it do so now. India, the prime minister said, is 
trying to mislead its own people and the international community 
by putting the blame on Pakistan for the situation in held 
Kashmir. Pakistan's policy of noninterference in the internal 
affairs of its neighbors, she added, proves Pakistan's respect 
for international law. Prime Minister Ms. Benazir Bhutto said 
India has launched a propaganda campaign that Pakistan is 
fanning trouble in occupied Kashmir. She said the indigenous 
movement in occupied Kashmir is being nurtured by the Kashmiris 
themselves and it is their spirit to render every sacrifice for 
their right of self-determination. She said Indian allegations 
were false and baseless and Pakistan has exposed Indian human 
rights violations in held Kashmir. 
  The prime minister regretted that the opposition tried to 
distort her every statement, but it would not deter her from 
serving the country. She urged the leader of the opposition to 
give up the negative attitude and work for promotion of 
consensus on national issues. Ms. Benazir Bhutto said the 
government and opposition may have political differences, but 
there should be consensus on issues of national importance. The 
prime minister said it was during Nawaz Sharif's tenure that 
Pakistan was blamed for terrorism despite the fact that India 
itself was indulging in human rights violations in held Kashmir. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

