<F P=101> Kuwait </F>
<H3> <TI>   Inclination Toward Cabinet Reshuffle Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1502150094 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 15 Feb 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM1502150094 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Ghunaym Muhammad al-Mutayri: "Inclination in </F>
Kuwait To Reshuffle Cabinet; Denial of Speculations About 
Government Resignation"] 
  [Excerpt] Kuwait -- Dr. Ya'qub Hayati, member of the 
Kuwaiti National Assembly Legislation and Legal Committee, has 
confirmed that there is an inclination to change some 
ministerial posts, including some ministers who are National 
Assembly members and others appointed by the prime minister. He 
added that these changes comes in response to requests submitted 
by a number of ministers recently. They asked to be relieved of 
their ministerial responsibilities. 
  In a statement to AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT, he pointed out that 
these requests have not been accepted because the country is 
going through a critical phase requiring complete cooperation 
among its members to return the situation to what it was before 
the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait. 
  He said that the picture has not yet become clear with 
regard 
to the ministers who are going to move to other posts inside the 
government. He stressed that the change will not include the 
Interior, Information, and Foreign Ministries. 
  Dr. Hayati said that "some ministers have not kept pace with 
the aspirations of the government, the people, and the National 
Assembly, thus new faces are needed -- faces capable of making 
decisions to reinforce the Kuwaiti citizens' confidence in the 
government." 
  However, Deputy Ahmad Baqir, secretary of the National 
Assembly, has denied recent media reports about a cabinet 
reshuffle. He told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT that this is "absolutely 
baseless." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

