<F P=100> Sudan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Denies Western `Allegations' of Offensive </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  EA1602205694 Omdurman National Unity Radio in English 1500 
GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> EA1602205694 </F>
<F P=104>  Omdurman National Unity Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Husayn Sulayman Abu-Salih affirmed 
the Sudanese Government's eagerness to achieve a peaceful 
solution to the southern problem. He stated that the government 
supports a ceasefire, provided that it is not used by the outlaw 
troops as camouflage for launching military offensives and 
subsequently hampering the peace endeavors. 
  Addressing the regular weekly forum of the Foreign Ministry 
yesterday, Dr. Abu-Salih said that many messages and statements 
recently had been issued by French, American, and UN 
personalities in relation to battles taking place in the south, 
noting that these messages and statements espoused that the 
Sudan Government was determined to end the southern question 
militarily. The foreign minister said that the miscarriage of 
the round of peace talks in Abuja two days ago was due to the 
interference of western circles, which are against the 
achievement of peace in Sudan. Dr. Abu-Salih described 
allegations of miltiary offensives by the government on 
civilians in the south as completely false and baseless. He 
added that John Garang and his companions are using civilians as 
human shields, referring to the outlaws' determination to keep 
ammunition stores and military at [words indistinct] and more 
civilian areas. Dr. Abu-Salih reiterated the government's 
commitment to cooperate with regard to delivering relief 
materials to war-affected citizens through Operation Lifeline, 
Sudan. 

</TEXT>

