<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Taba Negotiators Reportedly Nearing Agreement </TI></H3>
<H4>   Palestinian Negotiator on `Breakthrough' </H4>
<F P=102> JN1602171294 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Arabic 1530 GMT 16 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1602171294 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Khalid al-Qidrah, member of the Palestinian </F>
negotiating delegation and the Civilian Affairs Committee, by 
reporter Iyal 'Alima in Taba on 16 February; from the "With the 
Events" program -- recorded] 
  [Text] [Al-Qidrah] I believe that we are now in the final 
stages. The process of formulation will begin as soon as 
possible and will be followed by signature and implementation. 
I also believe that this will take place within a few weeks, or 
rather in some days before the end of this month. What is 
important, however, is that there is a real breakthrough, 
seriousness, and a desire for quick accomplishment in order to 
implement the Declaration of Principles as soon as possible. I 
do not believe that there are significant problems on any topic 
now. 
  ['Alima] Mr. Khalid al-Qidrah, member of the Palestinian 
delegation and the Civilian Affairs Committee: Apparently there 
is a breakthrough in some matters being discussed by this 
committee. Could you give us an idea in this regard? 
  [Al-Qidrah] In fact, the Civilian Affairs Committee began 
its work in this round of talks yesterday. Negotiations in all 
fields, even in the Security Committee, are proceeding in an 
intensive and serious manner and with a clear breakthrough and a 
real desire to achieve a full agreement in order to implement 
the Declaration of Principles as quickly as possible. 
  Yesterday and today, a review was made of all civil 
departments and issues which were not finalized in the previous 
rounds of negotiations. I believe that we have ended 
discussions on the public works department and electricity, and 
we are in the process of discussing the department of 
antiquities, population, and other issues. I also believe that 
these discussions will end because, as I said, work is taking 
place positively and with a desire to make an achievement and a 
breakthrough. 

</TEXT>

