<F P=101> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Romanians To Move From South After Attack on Bus </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1602205594 Paris AFP in English 1721 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1602205594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bucharest, Feb 16 (AFP)--A group of Romanian 
engineers who survived a gun attack are to quit southern Egypt 
after receiving threats from the main Muslim fundamentalist 
group al-Jama'ah al-Islamiyah, the Foreign Ministry said 
Wednesday. 
  The 20 Romanians working for a cement factory are to move 
from the southern Asyut region to the northern city of 
Alexandria until the situation calms down, ministry spokesman 
Mircea Geoana [name as received] said. 
  The engineers were on board a bus that was hit by gunfire on 
Monday near Asyut. They were unhurt, but the next day they 
received threats from the al-Jama'ah saying the shooting was 
only a warning. 
  The Egyptian authorities and the Romanian Embassy in Cairo 
were studying ways of protecting the 200 Romanians working in 
"sensitive" parts of the country, Geoana added. 
  Al-Jama'ah has warned foreigners to leave the country in its 
violent campaign against the government, which has claimed more 
than 300 lives. 

</TEXT>

