<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Saudi Decision To Purchase U.S. Planes Assessed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1702084094 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network in Persian 0445 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1702084094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Persian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Commentary by the News Research and Commentaries Group] </F>
  [Text] As was reported and was foreseeable, a Saudi bid for 
the purchase of dozens of passenger planes was handed to the 
U.S. company, Boeing. Saudi Arabia announced some months ago 
that it intended to purchase 60 planes to complete its 
passenger-plane fleet. Thus, it began talks with the U.S. 
companies Boeing and McDonnell Douglas, as well as with the 
European Airbus Consortium. 
  Political analysts believe that handing this bid over to the 
United States is more for political rather than commercial 
reasons, and that various elements were involved in this 
decision. The agreement of U.S. arms manufacturers one month 
ago to accept installment repayments of the military loans of 
Saudi Arabia, which was unable to repay its debts because of the 
drop in oil prices, is one of the most important elements. 
Also, the U.S. aircraft-manufacturing companies offered more 
benefits than their European competitors in an effort to 
maintain their world markets, especially under current 
conditions when White House officials are trying to help the 
U.S. economy emerge from its recession by expanding foreign 
markets. 
  Bill Clinton's contacts with King Fahd of Saudi Arabia may 
have been the most important reason why the bid for the purchase 
of dozens of passenger planes went to an American company. This 
contact--especially during the newly commenced economic war 
between the United States and Japan--is of great significance. 
Even though economic sanctions on Tokyo, which Clinton has 
threatened, would deprive Japan from the large U.S. market, it 
would also limit U.S. access to the Japanese market; this has 
set a new priority for U.S. economic policy of expanding its 
international markets as much as possible. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-34978 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes033_s_94003" </HT>


