<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Statement Criticizes President Clinton </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1702012294 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0035 
GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1702012294 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] India has said it is unfortunate that the U.S. 
President, Mr. Bill Clinton, had made common cause with Pakistan 
in his remarks on human rights in Jammu and Kashmir. An 
External Affairs Ministry statement issued last night said that 
Mr. Clinton has not taken into account the proven role of 
Pakistan as a state sponsoring terrorism, and no concern has 
been expressed for the human rights of the victims of the 
terrorists armed, trained, and sent into Jammu and Kashmir by 
Pakistan. The statement said that India is committed to uphold 
human rights as a part of its heritage and as enshrined in its 
Constitution and laws. 
  On the nuclear front, the statement said India neither had 
nor intended to acquire weapons of mass destruction. But 
Pakistan's nuclear intentions are well known and had been 
confirmed time and again. It said the real danger is not of an 
India-Pakistan nuclear exchange, but of nuclear adventurism on 
the part of Pakistan. 

</TEXT>

