<F P=100> LEBANON </F>
<H3> <TI>   Background of Jordanian Diplomat's Murder Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1602163094 Jerusalem AL-QUDS in Arabic 16 Feb 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> TA1602163094 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem AL-QUDS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Muhammad Dalbah] </F>
  [Text] Washington -- Suspicion about a Libyan connection 
in the assassination of Jordanian diplomat Na'ib al-Ma'ayitah in 
Beirut last month has been reinforced by reports that the 
Jordanian Government rejected a Libyan request to hand over two 
Libyan officers who had reportedly fled to Jordan in the wake of 
a failed coup attempt against Colonel Mu'ammar al-Qadhdhafi last 
October. 
  These reports state that two Libyan officers and a third 
person left for Jordan following the failure of this attempt and 
contacted the U.S. Embassy in Amman. 
  The two officers escaped across Libya's borders with a 
neighboring country on their way to Amman where they were joined 
by a civilian who was outside Libya when the detentions that 
followed the failed attempt were carried out. Two of the 
escapees belong to the al-Wa'ir clan, one of the most 
influential clans in the Libyan Warfalah tribe. 
  Libya demanded that the two officers be handed over, but the 
Jordanian authorities informed it that they were not in Amman. 
Actually, they had been transferred to a U.S. base in Germany 
where they were subjected to intense interrogation by U.S. 
agencies before being allowed to contact their friends in the 
Libyan opposition. 
  Libya, however, has denied any connection with the 
assassination of the Jordanian diplomat and has described 
reports linking it with the incident as an attempt to undermine 
its relations with Jordan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

