<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Data Shows Drop in `Terrorist' Attacks in Jerusalem </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1702110494 Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT in Hebrew 17 Feb 94 p 
16 </F>

<F P=103> TA1702110494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Doron Me'iri] </F>
  [Text] The number of terrorist attacks in Jerusalem fell 
sharply in 1993 compared with 1992. This emerges from data 
released by Yehuda Wilk, commander of the Israel Police 
Jerusalem District, summing up the 1993 work year. 
  The severity of the attacks, however, did not change: three 
people were killed and 17 wounded in 1993 compared with three 
killed and 12 wounded in 1992. 
  The number of car torchings dropped significantly: 267 cars 
were set ablaze in 1993 compared with 448 in 1992. Stone 
throwing also decreased sharply: 2,731 incidents in 1993 as 
opposed to 3,640 in 1992. The same applies to firebomb attacks: 
64 in 1993 as opposed to 91 in 1992. 
  There were 24 stabbings and attempted stabbings in 1993 
compared with 27 in 1992. Three bombs were planted in 1993 
compared with 14 in 1992. The number of shooting incidents 
remained unchanged: five instances in both 1992 and 1993. 
  Commander Wilk attributed the drop in terrorist attacks to 
"aggressive intelligence methods adopted by the Jerusalem 
police." According to him, "terror-related problems cannot be 
solved by deploying huge numbers of policemen and are best 
handled by small intelligence teams." 
  In 1993, the Jerusalem police arrested 350 Arabs suspected 
of 
having participated in disturbances, including stone-throwing 
incidents; 15 suspected of hurling firebombs; and 60 suspected 
of torching cars. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-35015 </DOCNO>
