<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Joining Government `Not on the Agenda' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1402052994 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 0500 GMT 14 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1402052994 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Coalition sources say that the possibility of 
Tzomet's and the National Religious Party's [NRP] joining the 
government is not on the agenda. Minister Yosi Sarid told our 
correspondent Yo'el Nir that this is a standard ritual we go 
through whenever there are problems in the opposition or one of 
its factions. 
  Our correspondent notes that according to one of the clauses 
in the coalition agreement, Meretz is entitled to veto the 
admission of any faction into the government. 
  SHAS [Torah Observing Sephardim] leader Arye Der'i says he 
will examine whether the possibility of Tzomet's and the NRP's 
joining the government is serious in order to determine whether 
it is time for SHAS to rejoin the coalition. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

