<F P=100> Libya </F>
<H3> <TI>   Radio Criticizes Arab Maghreb Union Inaction </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1702225694 Tripoli Libyan Television Network in Arabic 
2000 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1702225694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tripoli Libyan Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Today is the fifth anniversary of the declaration of 
the Arab Maghreb Union [AMU] between the Great Jamahiriyah, 
Tunisia, Algeria, Morocco, and Mauritania. On this day five 
years ago the treaty creating the AMU was signed at the 
Marrakesh summit in fraternal Morocco as a step on the road to 
achieving the all-embracing Arab unity. 
  The brother leader of the revolution emphasized at the final 
session of the Marrakesh summit the need to set up the AMU for 
the benefit of the toilers, the poor and the deprived who have 
suffered decades of oppression and colonialism, and to let the 
overwhelming majority [of the peoples of the Maghreb] have their 
share in the new unified Arab Maghreb. He also stressed that 
this Union should be a support for the struggle of the Arab 
Palestinian people for the liberation of Palestine from the 
river to the sea. 
  However, five years after its creation the treaty of this 
Union has remained mere ink on paper and its march has not 
achieved more than zero because it did not render any service to 
the Arab people in this region. Suffice to note that this union 
was incapable of holding a summit meeting and was unable to lift 
an unfair embargo imposed on a member state. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-35045 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes034_c_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-034 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ARAB AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Authorities Reportedly Arrest 942 Suspected `Militants' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1702173794 Paris AFP in English 1708 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1702173794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, Feb 17 (AFP)--Egyptian security forces 
rounded up more than 900 suspected Islamic militants in a 
countrywide sweep this week, the government daily AL-JUMHURIYAH 
reported Thursday. 
  The 942 people arrested included 38 known militants. 
  The raids, part of a campaign against Islamic 
fundamentalists 
battling the government, also netted 270 kilograms (595 pounds) 
of explosives and 920 weapons, the daily said. 

</TEXT>

