<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Palestinian, Israeli Negotiators Resume Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Delegates Discuss Police, Detainees </H4>
<F P=102> NC1702133694 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1145 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1702133694 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Taba, 17 Feb (MENA)--Palestinian and Israeli 
negotiators resumed their meetings in Taba this morning. Dr. 
Nabil Sha'th, political adviser to President Yasir 'Arafat, and 
General Amnon Shahaq, Israel's deputy chief of staff, led the 
talks that are trying to find a formula for the implementation 
of the Gaza-Jericho agreement. 
  MENA learned that the Security Committee was divided into 
two 
subcommittees. The first subcommittee is examining some details 
on the size of the Palestinian police force, the number of 
vehicles it will be using, and the nature of its tasks in Gaza 
and Jericho. 
  The other subcommittee is discussing the issue of 
Palestinian 
detainees in Israeli jails. Muhammad Dahlan, Palestinian 
security official in Gaza, and David Agmon, deputy security 
chief of the West Bank, head this subcommittee. 
  Dr. Sha'th last night met a delegation of the International 
Committee of the Red Cross [ICRC] operating in Israel and the 
occupied territories and reviewed with them a list of the 
Palestinian detainees. 
  An ICRC official said that he handed Dr. Sha'th a list of 
the 
Palestinian detainees and discussed with him humanitarian issues 
concerning the detainees. The official declined to divulge the 
number of Palestinian detainees. 
  Meanwhile, the Civilian Affairs Committee met for one hour 
today to continue discussing issues pertaining to electricity, 
historical sites, civil registration, and other unresolved 
issues. 
  Lawyer Jamil al-Tarifi said after the meeting that the 
committee reviewed what has already been agreed upon, namely the 
transfer of the electricity authority, civil registration, 
postal services, and public works to the Palestinians. He 
explained that issuing a postage stamp for local and 
international use will be left for the two leaderships in Tunis 
and Jerusalem to agree on. 
  Al-Tarifi added that progress has been made and the talks 
were conducted in a very positive atmosphere. He said 
communications, land registry, water resources, and historical 
sites will be discussed at the next round of talks, for which 
preparations were made during today's meeting. 
  The Security Committee is expected to end its meeting this 
afternoon. It will reconvene in Taba next Monday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-35049 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes034yy_94002" </HT>


