<H3> <TI>   Basindwah on Upcoming Signing Ceremonies in Amman </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN1702175994 Amman Radio Jordan Network in Arabic 1600 GMT 
17 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1702175994 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman Radio Jordan Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Political Forces Dialogue Committee in Yemen is 
meeting today to finalize travel arrangements to Amman where the 
accord agreement is scheduled to be signed next Sunday [20 
February]. It will be the committee's last meeting and will put 
the final touches on the measures leading up to the signing 
ceremonies. On the telephone from Yemen, the country's Foreign 
Minister Muhammad Salim Basindwah told our news desk: 
  [Begin Basindwah recording] It was only natural that we 
decide on Amman, the capital of brotherly Jordan, to be the 
venue for signing the accord document, in view of the key role 
played by Jordanian officials, above all His Majesty King 
Husayn, in the reconciliation effort. If the signing is not to 
take place on Yemeni territory, then Amman is the right choice. 
We hope that when the signing takes place on 10 Ramadan [20 
February] in Amman, it will mark the beginning of the end of the 
crisis that--had it not been for God's providence--would have 
pushed Yemen over the brink of disaster. I hope Amman's 
spiritual atmosphere in this favored month will rub off on the 
signing ceremonies. I am confident that his majesty's wisdom 
will go a long way toward a Yemeni reunion and the closing of 
ranks so we can pursue our constructive drive on the road to 
unity and democracy and a glorious and immortal Yemen will 
emerge, and, God willing, our country will be a source of 
strength and support for all its Arab brethren. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

