<H3> <TI>   Peres Sees Visit as `Positive Signal' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1802113694 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1005 GMT 18 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1802113694 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone interview with Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres by </F>
Gid'on Zelinger; place not given -- live] 
  [Excerpt] [Zelinger] We will now talk about the political 
agenda with Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres. Shalom to you, sir. 
  [Peres] Shalom. 
  [Zelinger] An Israeli delegation -- albeit one consisting of 
Israeli Arabs -- is due to depart for Syria. Will you ask 
Knesset Member 'Abd-al-Wahhab Darawshah or any other delegation 
member to convey any message to President al-Asad? 
  [Peres] I do not think that is necessary, because the 
purpose of this visit is to convey condolences. That was the 
reason cited in the application for permission to visit, and I 
think it should be honored. There is no need to turn a 
condolence visit into something else. Moreover, sending 
messages is not a problem. There are constant exchanges. 
  [Zelinger] I know Israel has been trying to open more than 
one channel of negotiations with Syria. 
  [Peres] That is correct. I know that on this occasion, 
however, the visas were granted for the purpose of calling on 
the bereaved family, and this should be honored. 
  [Zelinger] Would you like to comment on the very fact of the 
visit? Is the departure of an Israeli delegation to Damascus an 
important event? 
  [Peres] I think it is a positive signal and I welcome it, 
although it has its limitations. It does not yet herald a burst 
of possibilities. It is a signal -- a positive and not at all 
negligible one -- but that is all it is. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

