<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Calls For Golan Heights' Return to Syria </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1602172894 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1540 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1602172894 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 16 Feb (MENA)--Shulamit Aloni, Israeli 
director of scientific research and communications [title as 
received], has called for the return of the occupied Golan 
Heights to Syria. She has also expressed her opposition to the 
idea of holding a referendum on withdrawal from the Heights, 
stressing that the Israeli Government has full authority to make 
a political decision without the need for a referendum. 
  In an interview to be published in the 17 February issue of 
the magazine AL-MUSAWWAR, she said that in accordance with 
international law, the Golan Heights must return to Syria. She 
indicated that the problem with the negotiations lies in the 
timeframe and the security arrangements. 
  The Israeli minister criticized the Israeli Government's 
lukewarm reaction to the Geneva summit between Syrian President 
Hafiz al-Asad and U.S. President Bill Clinton. 
  On the Israeli request for a meeting between President 
al-Asad and Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin, Aloni 
explained that such a meeting might set things in motion. 
  On Israel's arbitrary measures in the occupied territories, 
Aloni said: In my opinion, we as a people are living with a 
sharp moral dilemma. We speak about democracy and human rights 
while we rob the Palestinian people of their rights. She 
indicated that the mutual recognition between Israel and the PLO 
will entrench equality and mutual respect. 
  Regarding armaments and nuclear deterrents, Aloni said: 
Israel's fears are from Iran and Iraq. These fears extend to 
the whole region. So Israel is arming itself with long-range 
weapons that act as a deterrent against Iraq and Iran and, to 
some extent, against Syria. She indicated that after progress 
is made in the peace process, this topic will be submitted for 
discussion with Egypt and Syria. 
  On Israel's withdrawal from south Lebanon, Aloni said Israel 
has no ambitions in Lebanon. It will withdraw from south 
Lebanon when peace is established with Syria. 

</TEXT>

