<H3> <TI>   Beilin: Only Humanitarian Aid for UN Missions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1702080494 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in English 0500 GMT 17 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1702080494 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Israel has informed the UN secretary general it is 
ready to set up and maintain a hospital in Angola. Deputy 
Foreign Minister Yosi Beilin also told reporter David Essing 
that Israel has decided not to participate in international 
peacekeeping missions abroad. 
  [Begin recording] [Beilin] Our only decision is to take 
part in humanitarian efforts in Angola. We are ready to do 
that, and I will inform the UN secretary general about that 
decision. Maybe later on, in due time, such a decision that you 
are referring to will be taken, but time is not ripe now to take 
it. 
  [Essing] What kind of participation will Israel be giving to 
this Angolan project? 
  [Beilin] We are speaking about establishing and controlling 
a hospital in Angola, sending doctors and some other medical 
services to Angola, and to keep this hospital for a while. 
  [Essing] Any time frame for this? When will this be taking 
place? 
  [Beilin] There are still many conditions, and the first one 
is that there will be peace in Angola. This is far from being 
the reality, and the fighting between Savimbi and Dos Santos in 
Angola still takes place, so we cannot know exactly the timing 
of such a decision, but it won't be tomorrow. [end recording] 
  In an address last night, Beilin said also that two 
representatives of countries he declined to name recently 
visited Israel seeking advice and training in the resolution of 
disputes. He did not elaborate. 

</TEXT>

