<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials, Radio Comment on Rushdie Fatwa Anniversary </TI></H3>
<H4>   Execution Said `Least Punishment' </H4>
<F P=102> LD1602233194 </F>
<F P=103> LD1602233194 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of 
Iran First Program Network in Persian at 1600 GMT on 16 February 
broadcasts a 30-minute weekly news review program entitled 
"Seven Days, The World." This week's program includes a 
six-minute section on the 14 February anniversary of Ayatollah 
Khomeyni's fatwa calling for Salman Rushdie's death for writing 
the book The Satanic Verses. 
  After reviewing the reasons and results of the fatwa, the 
announcer states: "A coordinated endeavor by the Western media 
focuses on the revival of a current, a current which has been 
practically buried since the issuance of the fatwa. Now, from 
that defeated ploy, only a plaything is left which every now and 
then comes out of its hiding-place, for a few moments, to create 
propaganda fodder for the Western propaganda horns. 
  "In any case the conspiracy of the insulting book, The 
Satanic Verses, was an insult against the beliefs and 
sanctities of more than one billion Muslims which can never be 
explained within the limits of freedom of thought and freedom of 
the pen. The least punishment for a mercenary who carried out 
that plot, is the irrevocable decree for his execution." 

</TEXT>

