<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Foreign Ministry Appointment Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1702120194 Tehran TEHRAN TIMES in English 15 Feb 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> NC1702120194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran TEHRAN TIMES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the TEHRAN TIMES city desk] </F>
  [Text] Tehran--Foreign Minister Dr. 'Ali Akbar Velayati 
formally issued orders yesterday for the appointment of Mohammad 
Hashemi as his first deputy. 
  It is expected that former head of the Islamic Republic of 
Iran Broadcasting will takeover the second most important and 
sensitive post today. 
  Hashemi was replaced on Sunday by former Minister of Islamic 
Culture and Guidance Dr. 'Ali Larijani. 
  The post is qa'em-maqam, as it is called in Persian, since 
the first deputy traditionally has no specific or defined duties. 
  'Ali Mohammad Besharati held the post before being appointed 
interior minister by President 'Ali Akbar Hashemi-Rafsanjani 
last August. 
  Besharati, a member of the Islamic Consultative Assembly, 
the 
Majles, during its First Term, was appointed first deputy at the 
Foreign Ministry in 1983. During his term of office, he was 
assigned Persian Gulf affairs by Dr. Velayati. 
  It is popularly believed that Besharati was more than 
successful in his mission despite transparent Western schemes to 
keep a rift between Iran and the Arab countries on the other 
side of the Persian Gulf. 
  It will be interesting to see what particular assignment is 
given to Hashemi. The former student of the University of 
California, Berkeley, could be a big help to Dr. Velayati 
because of his awareness of the West and America in particular. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

