<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Secret' PLO-Israeli Talks Begin in Cairo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2102135294 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1320 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2102135294 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 21 Feb (MENA)--Palestinian and Israeli 
negotiators started in Cairo today a new round of talks on the 
final arrangements for temporary Palestinian self-rule in the 
Gaza Strip and Jericho. 
  The talks began with a private meeting between Dr. Nabil 
Sha'th, political adviser to Palestinian President Yasir 
'Arafat, and General Amnon Shahaq, Israeli deputy chief of 
staff, to draw up the agenda of the talks. 
  Afterward, the meeting of the Security Affairs Committee 
began under Dr. Sha'th and General Shahaq. The Civilian Affairs 
Committee also met under attorney Jamil al-Tarifi representing 
the Palestinian side and Gadi Zohar representing the Israeli 
side. 
  Ya'qov Neriah, political adviser to Israeli Prime Minister 
Yitzhaq Rabin, is participating in the talks for the first time. 
  Palestinian sources said Y'aqov Neriah's participation in 
the 
talks means the Israeli side is serious about reaching an 
agreement on the points of differences still under discussion. 
The sources noted the positive atmosphere and the great 
progress made during the last round of talks in Taba. 
  Hasan 'Asfur and Y'aqov Neriah told journalists that the 
talks will be held in secret and that the press will not be 
allowed to cover them. The Palestinian and Israeli negotiators 
will hold intensive talks until Wednesday, when Sha'th and 
Shahaq will announce the results at a news conference. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

