<H3> <TI>   Police Chief Denies Favoritism in Recruiting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN2002205994 Sanaa Voice of Palestine in Arabic 1800 GMT 20 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2002205994 </F>
<F P=104>  Sanaa Voice of Palestine </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Colonel Ibrahim Muhanna, commander of the 
Palestinian police force in the Gaza strip, has denied the 
affiliations of applicants to the force make a difference in 
their chances of appointment. 
  He told the BBC that candidates for appointment to the 
police 
force are selected in accordance with Palestinian law and draft 
regulations. He indicated that out of approximately 11,000 
candidates who have applied to join the Palestinian police 
force, 3,000 have so far passed the medical test. I have no 
right to ask any applicant about his affiliation, he stressed. 
  Muhanna indicated that the spread of arms carries grave 
risks 
for the Palestinian people. When Palestinian police are 
deployed in the occupied territories, they will operate under a 
Palestinian penal code, and law breakers will be prosecuted. 
Muhanna noted that, in certain respects, that there is 
cooperation between Palestinian police and Israeli authorities. 

</TEXT>

