<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   PFLP Official Denies Habash, 'Arafat Meeting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN2102112194 Amman AL-RA'Y in Arabic 21 Feb 94 p 23 </F>
<F P=103> JN2102112194 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AL-RA'Y </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Amman, QUDS PRESS -- An official of the Popular 
Front for the Liberation of Palestine [PFLP] has said there are 
no arrangements to hold a meeting between PFLP Secretary General 
George Habash and Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat. 
  In a telephone interview with QUDS PRESS, 'Abd-al-Rahim 
Malluh, member of the PFLP Political Bureau, denied reports 
about an upcoming meeting between 'Arafat and Habash. Malluh 
said these reports are groundless. 
  Palestinian sources close to Fatah had spoken about a 
meeting 
to be held between the two Palestinian leaders who arrived in 
Amman to attend a Yemeni reconciliation meeting. 
  Malluh said the PFLP still thinks there is no political 
common ground to hold such a meeting. He said: Our dispute 
with Yasir 'Arafat -- over the Palestinian-Israeli Declaration 
of Principles reached in Oslo and the Cairo agreement on 
implementing the self-rule in Gaza and Jericho -- precludes any 
common ground for a meeting with him, as Malluh put it. 
  The PFLP is opposed to a self-rule agreement struck between 
the PLO and Israel and signed in Washington on 13 September. 
Like other opposition factions, the PFLP refuses to hold any 
meeting with the PLO leadership before annulling this agreement 
and subsequent accords. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

