  [Text] Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres said today that he 
does not share the assessment that Egyptian President Mubarak's 
regime is threatened. Our correspondent Hayim Hecht reports 
that in a meeting with the Labor Knesset caucus, Peres said that 
Mubarak's regime handles fundamentalist violence with political 
wisdom and appropriate force. Peres stressed that signs of 
economic development are clearly visible in Egypt. 
  The foreign minister sharply attacked the Syrian attitude 
toward the peace process. He said that we have a right to 
demand that it raise the level of negotiators to that of heads 
of state or senior ministers. The Syrians must adjust to 
international standards. We will not get far if we continue the 
Syrian way of negotiating. The talks with them are still bogged 
down, Peres said. 

